You could try something like this:

    public void removeBytesFromStart(ByteBuffer bf, int n) {
        int index = 0;
        for(int i = n; i &lt; bf.position(); i++) {
            bf.put(index++, bf.get(i));
            bf.put(i, (byte)0);
        }
        bf.position(index);
    }

Or something like this:

    public void removeBytesFromStart2(ByteBuffer bf, int n) {
        int index = 0;
        for(int i = n; i &lt; bf.limit(); i++) {
            bf.put(index++, bf.get(i));
            bf.put(i, (byte)0);
        }
        bf.position(bf.position()-n);
    }

This uses the absolute [get][1] and [put][2] method of the [ByteBuffer][3] class and sets the [position][4] at next write position.

Note that the absolute `put` method is optional, which means that a class that extends the abstract class `ByteBuffer` may not provide an implementation for it, for example it might throw a `ReadOnlyBufferException`.

Whether you choose to loop till [position][5] or till [limit][6] depends on how you use the buffer, for example if you manually set the [position][7] you might want to use loop till `limit`. If you do not then looping till `position` is enough and more efficient.

